    <a href="/reading/natural-breadcrumbs/" class="text-sm mb-4 inline-block">← back to index</a>

    <h1>Combining Effects and Coeffects via Grading</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mb-6">Gaboardi, Katsumata, Orchard, Sato · ESOP 2021 · <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2007.06237"><img src="/reading/arxiv.webp" alt="arxiv" style="display:inline;height:1em;vertical-align:-0.1em;margin-right:0.2em;"/> arXiv:2007.06237</a></p>

    <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 mb-6">Prereqs: <a href="/reading/natural-breadcrumbs/staton-2025/">🍞 Staton 2025</a> (Hoare triples). 5 min.</p>

    <div class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-5 mb-8 callout">
      <p class="text-lg" style="max-width:none">Hoare triples with <strong>grades</strong>: a tag on every computation tracking side effects: how many resources it uses, how much noise it adds, how far it can branch. The grade algebra tells you what happens when you compose.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- 1. Grades track effects -->
    <h3>Grades track effects</h3>
    <p>A grade is an annotation on a computation. Plain Hoare logic says <code>{'{P}'} c {'{Q}'}</code>. Graded Hoare logic says <code>{'{P}'} c : e {'{Q}'}</code> — "c has effect e." When you compose, the grades compose too: if c₁ has grade e₁ and c₂ has grade e₂, then c₁;c₂ has grade e₁·e₂ (monoid multiplication).</p>

    <!-- SVG: Graded Hoare triple -->
